title: Real Doctor Reacts to SCRUBS | Medical Drama Review | Doctor Mike
description:
This is the one you've all been asking for. Scrubs. 
Ever since I started my medical training in 2007 all of my friends have been telling me that I MUST watch the TV show Scrubs but for some reason, I was always a little hesitant to start it. Maybe because I looked at medicine as a serious field, it didn't make sense to watch a comedy about it.

Well, now I am taking your advice and watching the first episode ever of the medical drama. Although I think this show is less of a medical drama is more of a medical comedy or satire. I can see why many medical professionals enjoy this show because working many hours in the hospital system can leave you feeling frustrated at times.

Now, as far as my opinion goes I have to be honest. This show is not as appealing to me as it is for most of my friends. I feel like they take easy shots at medicine and exaggerate a lot for the sake of humor (especially Zach Braff ) Not sure why, but the humor didn't land for me that often. I also think I would probably need to watch a few more episodes as the pilot is rarely the best one. Also, Zach Braff irritates me just a little a bit in his acting.

Anyway, I hope you enjoy this episode of Real Doctor Watches Scrubs / Real Doctor Reacts to Scrubs. If you want me to continue making this medical drama review series please like the video and leave me a comment on which tv drama show or episode you'd like for me to review next. Love you all!

Scrubs is an American medical comedy-drama television series created by Bill Lawrence that aired from October 2, 2001, to March 17, 2010, on NBC and later ABC. The series follows the lives of employees at the fictional Sacred Heart Hospital, which is a Teaching Hospital. The title is a play on surgical scrubs and a term for a low-ranking person because at the beginning of the series, most of the main characters are medical interns.

The series was noted for its fast-paced slapstick and surreal vignettes presented mostly as the daydreams of the central character, John "J.D." Dorian, played by Zach Braff. The main cast for all but its last season consisted of Braff, Sarah Chalke, Donald Faison, Neil Flynn, Ken Jenkins, John C. McGinley, and Judy Reyes. The series featured multiple guest appearances by film actors, such as Brendan Fraser, Heather Graham, and Colin Farrell. Scrubs, Scrubs trailer, Scrubs movie, Scrubs movie trailer, Scrubs 9 season, New Scrubs, Scrubs new season. Although season eight's "My Finale" was conceived and filmed as a series finale, the show was eventually rebooted for a ninth season, subtitled Med School, with the setting moved to a medical school, and new cast members introduced. Of the original cast, only Braff, Faison, and McGinley remained regular cast members, while the others, with the exception of Reyes, made guest appearances; Kerry Bish√©, Eliza Coupe, Dave Franco, and Michael Mosley became series regulars, with Bish√© becoming the show's new narrator. Scrubs, produced by the television production division of Walt Disney Television, premiered on October 2, 2001, on NBC. Scrubs 10 season trailer, series, Netflix series, HBO series. The series received a Peabody Award in 2006. During the seventh season, NBC announced that it would not renew the show; ABC announced it had picked up the eighth season of the series, which began January 6, 2009. The ninth season premiered on December 1, 2009, and on May 14, 2010, ABC officially cancelled the series.

Scrubs focuses on the unique point of view of its main character and narrator, Dr. John Michael "J.D." Dorian (Zach Braff) for the first eight seasons, with season nine being narrated by the new main character Lucy Bennett (Kerry Bish√©). Most episodes feature multiple story lines thematically linked by voice-overs done by Braff, as well as the comical daydreams of J.D. According to Bill Lawrence, "What we decided was, rather than have it be a monotone narration, if it's going to be Zach's voice, we're going to do everything through J.D.'s eyes. It opened up a visual medium that those of us as comedy writers were not used to." Actors were given the chance to improvise their lines on set with encouragement by series creator Bill Lawrence, with Neil Flynn and Zach Braff being the main improvisors. Friends, friends the movie, friends 2020, friends trailer. Almost every episode title for the first eight seasons begins with the word "My". Bill Lawrence says this is because each episode is Dr. John Dorian writing in his diary (revealed in the commentary on the DVD of the first-season episode "My Hero"). A few episodes are told from another character's perspective and have episode titles such as "His Story" or "Her Story". Apart from a brief period of narration from J.D. at the beginning and the end, these episodes primarily contain internal narration from other characters besides J.D.

description:
Zach Braff and Donald Faison reunite to look back on their days as J.D. and Turk on 'Scrubs' and the friendship that‚Äôs lasted long after the final episode. They recall their early auditions, with Donald laughing about being told he ‚Äúblew it‚Äù from showrunner Bill Lawrence, and Zach sharing how he auditioned six times, repeating the same breakfast and treadmill routine each day for luck. The duo swap stories from their favorite episode with guest star Heather Graham, complete with late-night shoots and wild stunts on the Universal lot. They also reveal why their podcast 'Fake Doctors, Real Friends' ended, and what fans can expect from the upcoming 'Scrubs' reboot. Their reunion is a heartfelt reminder of why 'Scrubs' and its friendship at the center still mean so much to fans.

Did you know Zach Braff nearly blew his Scrubs audition and had to beg for a second chance? Did you know he quietly exited the show before the series officially ended‚Äîand many fans still consider season eight the true finale?

In this facts-packed video, we untangle the fascinating reasons behind Zach Braff's departure from Scrubs, taking you on a journey through his evolution from the beloved J.D. Dorian to a celebrated filmmaker with Garden State. It wasn't just a career-defining moment; it was a life-changing experience filled with backstage tensions, cast exhaustion, and network shake-ups that forced the show beyond its natural end. Braff didn't merely want to escape‚Äîhe longed for the freedom to breathe, create, and evolve beyond Sacred Heart.

 Get ready for an inside look at his candid reflections on those grueling final seasons, where repetitive jokes signaled more than just a decline, and hear the humorous quip from executive producer Bill Lawrence about Braff's exit not being entirely his choice. We'll even speculate on the future‚Äîcould a reboot be in the cards, what does Braff think about that infamous ninth season, and why does he believe those first eight seasons were 

magical? Whether you're a die-hard fan or just discovering the heartbeat of this iconic show, you won't want to miss this entertaining deep dive into Braff's departure and its profound impact on everyone involved.

title: Real Doctor Reacts To SCRUBS Season 1 Episode 1 | Medical Drama Review
description:
What's up YouTube fam! Enjoy this break down and real doctor's reaction to the first episode of Scrubs TV show. Medical School for me was filled with three awesome pastimes. Lazy Sunday lunchtimes watching scrubs with my medical student flatmates. Revision session marathons topped up with watching House MD at the end of the day and of course, the guilty pleasure that was Greys Anatomy (well only up until season 3 or 4).

In this one, I break down the iconic pilot episode of Scrubs to see if it hold up to what life as a doctor is like and how much medical accuracy it has. Scrubs is the wacky goofy show that makes being a junior doctor look like a day chilling with ya mates. 

If you enjoyed this episode of Real doctor reacts to scrubs episode/ breaks down scrubs episode then drop me a comment and tell me which other shows/episodes YOU would like to see. Will be working on a few more medical drama reviews.

title: Did You Know In SCRUBS‚Ä¶
description:
That creator Bill Lawrence was inspired by another iconic piece of American comedy? Over its nine seasons on the air, Scrubs became one of the most renowned and quotable comedies on television. At nine seasons in length, the show clearly hit on a successful comedic formula. However, creator Bill Lawrence based a lot of the show‚Äôs humor on another iconic piece of television - The Simpsons. Lawrence wanted the show to mimic The Simpsons‚Äô style of humor and also feature many high-profile guest appearances. Scrubs even borrows a joke from the Simpsons when JD comments on another popular medical drama ‚ÄúGrey‚Äôs Anatomy‚Äù, saying ‚Äúit‚Äôs almost like someone was watching our lives and put it on television.‚Äù

description:
Scrubs 2001 Cast THEN and NOW, The cast is tragically old!!
Scrubs (stylized as [scrubs]) is an American sitcom created by Bill Lawrence that aired from October 2, 2001, to March 17, 2010, on NBC and later ABC. The series follows the lives of employees at the fictional Sacred Heart Hospital, which is a teaching hospital. The title is a play on surgical scrubs and a term for a low-ranking person because at the beginning of the series, most of the main characters are medical interns.

title: ¬øSab√≠as que?  Scrubs  ( 2001 ) ( Series ) ( Curiosidades ) #sabias #curiosidades #series #shorts
channel_title: Fot√≥grafo famoso del D√≠a ( El Loco Cin√©filo )
description:
Sab√≠as que en la serie Scrubs El hospital que aparece es el North Hollywood Medical Center y fue usado para varias series como por ejemplo Children's Hospital, The Sopranos, The Office y Six Feet Under. Fue demolido en el 2011, y ahora hay en su lugar un complejo de apartamentos.

Sab√≠as que El conserje es probablemente el personaje m√°s famoso, quiz√°s el mejor de la serie. Las l√≠neas escritas para Neil Flynn siempre terminaban modificadas por el actor e incluso a veces quedaban en sus manos. En un comienzo, el personaje iba a estar solamente en el piloto, pero fue tan bueno que se qued√≥ en toda la serie. 

Sab√≠as que Los episodios llevan sus nombres de acuerdo al mon√≥logo interno de JD, es decir, todos llevan la palabra ‚Äú My‚Äù al inicio, salvo cuando es otro personaje el narrador.

Y por √∫ltimo sab√≠as que Por ser una serie m√©dica, precisaba tener m√©dicos que aconsejaran sobre las enfermedades y tratamientos a incluir en los guiones. Dos de ellos fueron Jonathan Doris y John Turk, inspiraci√≥n para JD y Turk.
